00:39:33.217 --> 00:39:35.050
TOBIAS CARLISLE: Well,
I'm sure that he has.

00:39:35.050 --> 00:39:36.540
AUDIENCE: But, OK, OK.

00:39:36.540 --> 00:39:37.040
I guess--

00:39:37.040 --> 00:39:38.340
TOBIAS CARLISLE: So
why do it that way?

00:39:38.340 --> 00:39:39.355
Well, you know there are--

00:39:39.355 --> 00:39:41.040
AUDIENCE: You understand
my question, yeah.

00:39:41.040 --> 00:39:41.360
TOBIAS CARLISLE: I do.

00:39:41.360 --> 00:39:42.930
There are elements
to the business.

00:39:42.930 --> 00:39:46.070
It's a marketing business as
much as it's a return business.

00:39:46.070 --> 00:39:47.850
AUDIENCE: But I
have the impression

00:39:47.850 --> 00:39:49.760
that Joel Greenblatt
doesn't really--

00:39:49.760 --> 00:39:51.850
I mean, he has enough
money and he doesn't really

00:39:51.850 --> 00:39:54.290
care about making more money.

00:39:54.290 --> 00:39:57.560
I mean, I could be wrong.

00:39:57.560 --> 00:40:02.680
TOBIAS CARLISLE: In different
states of the world,

00:40:02.680 --> 00:40:05.230
the magic formula will
outperform the earnings yield.

00:40:05.230 --> 00:40:09.620
So when the markets are
racing up, in a bull market,

00:40:09.620 --> 00:40:10.641
it's about even.

00:40:10.641 --> 00:40:12.140
But there are some
periods of time--

00:40:12.140 --> 00:40:14.220
the late 1990s
for example, which

00:40:14.220 --> 00:40:16.720
was an unusual period in the
markets-- but the magic formula

00:40:16.720 --> 00:40:19.320
did outperform the
