00:53:16.496 --> 00:53:18.620
about a company, and they
rank all of the companies

00:53:18.620 --> 00:53:21.330
on the basis of how
liked or hated they are,

00:53:21.330 --> 00:53:24.010
then they examine their
performance the following year.

00:53:24.010 --> 00:53:26.340
The most hated companies
outperform the most admired

00:53:26.340 --> 00:53:27.590
companies.

00:53:27.590 --> 00:53:30.080
Morningstar gives
rankings to companies,

00:53:30.080 --> 00:53:33.550
this is an A company, A plus,
this one's a B, this one's a D,

00:53:33.550 --> 00:53:36.530
this one's an E. The
Es comprehensively

00:53:36.530 --> 00:53:38.350
outperform the As.

00:53:38.350 --> 00:53:40.210
Every single time
you look at research,

00:53:40.210 --> 00:53:42.241
and it's so counter
to everything

00:53:42.241 --> 00:53:43.990
you see everywhere
else, where everybody's

00:53:43.990 --> 00:53:47.200
saying find the really
high quality ones.

00:53:47.200 --> 00:53:51.920
So I didn't go looking for it.

00:53:51.920 --> 00:53:54.430
But when you look at this
sort of strategy outside

00:53:54.430 --> 00:53:56.570
of this market, you find
almost the same thing.

00:53:56.570 --> 00:53:58.360
The one exception
to that is Japan.

00:53:58.360 --> 00:54:00.550
For whatever reason,
the magic formula

00:54:00.550 --> 00:54:02.670
over the period of the
data that we examined

00:54:02.670 --> 00:54:04.860
outperformed the
earnings yield alone.

00:54:04.860 --> 00:54:08.500
Japan's an outlier in a number
of different strategies.

00:54:08.500 --> 00:54:10.642
Momentum hasn't worked
in Japan, whereas that's

00:54:10.642 --> 00:54:11.975
worked in lots of other markets.

00:54:14.596 --> 00:54:16.720
Even though Japan has sort
of been gently falling--

00:54:16.720 --> 00:54:20.630
this is just an interesting
side comment-- even though it's

00:54:20.630 --> 00:54:24.280
been gently falling since
1990, value investing

00:54:24.280 --> 00:54:26.387
strategies in Japan
have worked really well,

00:54:26.387 --> 00:54:28.720
just buying the cheapest
companies on the basis of price

00:54:28.720 --> 00:54:31.210
to earnings, price to
cash flow, price to book

00:54:31.210 --> 00:54:33.760
has done something
like 20% a year.

00:54:33.760 --> 00:54:37.890
So the magic formula might have
just captured a little bit more

00:54:37.890 --> 00:54:39.447
of that performance.

00:54:39.447 --> 00:54:41.030
But yes, there's
always a risk of data

00:54:41.030 --> 00:54:43.340
mining in this sort of stuff.

00:54:43.340 --> 00:54:46.600
I think that the acquirer's
multiple is the way

00:54:46.600 --> 00:54:48.830
that value investors
think about investing.

00:54:48.830 --> 00:54:50.850
So if you think about
the way that you're

00:54:50.850 --> 00:54:53.330
instructed in "Security
Analysis" or "The Intelligent

00:54:53.330 --> 00:54:54.955
Investor" or any of
Buffett's letters,

00:54:54.955 --> 00:54:57.960
he says think about
buying the company,

00:54:57.960 --> 00:55:00.056
and it's think about
buying the entire business.

00:55:00.056 --> 00:55:02.680
You're not buying a share of it,
you're buying the whole thing.

00:55:02.680 --> 00:55:05.725
And that's exactly what the
acquirer's multiple does.

00:55:05.725 --> 00:55:08.280
It says, this is what you pay
for the market capitalization,

00:55:08.280 --> 00:55:11.960
but don't forget that you've got
preferred stock, debt, minority

00:55:11.960 --> 00:55:14.110
interests, off balance
sheet liabilities,

00:55:14.110 --> 00:55:17.271
underfunded pensions, other
things that you have to fund.

00:55:17.271 --> 00:55:19.020
But you get the benefit
of the cash that's

00:55:19.020 --> 00:55:21.210
sitting in the bank,
all the net cash,

00:55:21.210 --> 00:55:22.780
and then you have
this discretion

00:55:22.780 --> 00:55:26.250
to spend the operating earnings
as they're coming in on capex

00:55:26.250 --> 00:55:28.740
or paying down debt, or
various other things.

00:55:28.740 --> 00:55:31.310
So it's looking
at the same thing

00:55:31.310 --> 00:55:34.630
that big acquirers
look at, and I often

00:55:34.630 --> 00:55:37.280
find that I'm in positions
that somebody else has

00:55:37.280 --> 00:55:38.870
been buying right behind me.

00:55:38.870 --> 00:55:41.280
It's a Carl Icahn
or another activist,

00:55:41.280 --> 00:55:42.370
or a private equity firm.

00:55:42.370 --> 00:55:43.530
Something happens in them.

00:55:43.530 --> 00:55:45.680
Because when they
get very cheap,

00:55:45.680 --> 00:55:49.580
there's a little
bit of instability.

00:55:49.580 --> 00:55:51.970
It's not a situation that
should persist like that.

00:55:51.970 --> 00:55:54.550
There's sort of inviting
external managers

00:55:54.550 --> 00:55:58.600
to come in and try to
rectify the situation.

00:55:58.600 --> 00:56:00.550
Data mining is always
a problem, but I

00:56:00.550 --> 00:56:02.050
think there are a
variety of reasons

00:56:02.050 --> 00:56:03.830
why this strategy
should work quite well,

00:56:03.830 --> 00:56:06.410
and it does work quite well
in different time periods

00:56:06.410 --> 00:56:07.865
and in different markets.

00:56:07.865 --> 00:56:10.890
AUDIENCE: Buffett talks
about holding stocks

00:56:10.890 --> 00:56:12.750
for the long term,
and one of the reasons

00:56:12.750 --> 00:56:15.260
that he likes it is because
of the tax consequences.

00:56:15.260 --> 00:56:17.560
Can you talk a little
bit about the difference

00:56:17.560 --> 00:56:19.480
between trying to find
companies that you

00:56:19.480 --> 00:56:21.850
can hold for a long period
of time versus rebalancing

00:56:21.850 --> 00:56:23.485
and using the deep
value strategy?

00:56:23.485 --> 00:56:25.360
TOBIAS CARLISLE: This
is one of the arguments

00:56:25.360 --> 00:56:29.280
for-- this is what the franchise
investors are trying to do.

00:56:29.280 --> 00:56:30.890
They want to buy
that company that

00:56:30.890 --> 00:56:35.610
can sustain those very high
returns on invested capital,

00:56:35.610 --> 00:56:40.100
and ideally grow and compound
away, throwing off cash

00:56:40.100 --> 00:56:44.690
while they're doing it so that
10 years or 20 years from now,

00:56:44.690 --> 00:56:46.730
you're getting out
of it in dividends

00:56:46.730 --> 00:56:48.290
what you invested
in it, and it's

00:56:48.290 --> 00:56:50.960
a much more valuable company.

00:56:50.960 --> 00:56:53.457
So if you think about the
process of going and finding

00:56:53.457 --> 00:56:55.290
one of those companies,
knowing that there's

00:56:55.290 --> 00:56:58.667
that mean reversion in
return on invested capital,

00:56:58.667 --> 00:56:59.750
what would you rather buy?

00:56:59.750 --> 00:57:02.710
Do you want to buy one that has
a very high return on invested

00:57:02.710 --> 00:57:05.770
capital that might mean revert,
or are you better off finding

00:57:05.770 --> 00:57:08.470
one that's very cheap,
that might be at a trough,

00:57:08.470 --> 00:57:11.410
that you can hold
for seven or eight

00:57:11.410 --> 00:57:14.670
or nine or ten years
that reverts up.

00:57:14.670 --> 00:57:17.890
I think you've got as
much chance of selecting.

00:57:17.890 --> 00:57:20.507
The challenge is
not to buy something

00:57:20.507 --> 00:57:22.090
that looks like it's
high quality now,

00:57:22.090 --> 00:57:24.720
the challenge is to
buy something and hold

00:57:24.720 --> 00:57:26.160
something that is high quality.

00:57:26.160 --> 00:57:28.010
So we all want to
buy the same stocks.

00:57:28.010 --> 00:57:29.030
Maybe I haven't made
that clear enough.

00:57:29.030 --> 00:57:30.860
We all want, I want
to buy, everybody

00:57:30.860 --> 00:57:32.780
wants to buy the really
high-- everybody wants

00:57:32.780 --> 00:57:34.450
to own the really
high quality stock,

00:57:34.450 --> 00:57:36.920
the compounding machine that
has the very high returns

00:57:36.920 --> 00:57:38.280
on invested capital.

00:57:38.280 --> 00:57:42.320
But can you use historical
data to identify them?

00:57:42.320 --> 00:57:43.260
It's not clear.

00:57:43.260 --> 00:57:45.096
But what is clear is
that buying the ones

00:57:45.096 --> 00:57:46.720
with higher returns
on invested capital

00:57:46.720 --> 00:57:50.230
don't necessarily
turn into ones that

00:57:50.230 --> 00:57:53.112
have high returns on invested
capital subsequently.

00:57:53.112 --> 00:57:56.070
AUDIENCE: So one thing you
talk about in the book is,

00:57:56.070 --> 00:57:57.900
one of the reasons
this strategy works

00:57:57.900 --> 00:58:02.320
is because of activist investors
are kind of arbitraging

00:58:02.320 --> 00:58:09.160
into an alternate market where
companies are being traded, not

00:58:09.160 --> 00:58:11.210
because they want the
stock to trade high,

00:58:11.210 --> 00:58:14.010
but because they want to
take control of the company.

00:58:14.010 --> 00:58:16.390
And so activism is a
pretty important kind

00:58:16.390 --> 00:58:18.510
of catalyst to this strategy.

00:58:18.510 --> 00:58:23.170
What do you think about this
strategy working for companies

00:58:23.170 --> 00:58:26.830
where the incumbent management
is an owner operator,

00:58:26.830 --> 00:58:28.770
and they have motivations
that are completely

00:58:28.770 --> 00:58:32.870
independent of the minority
shareholder motivations,

00:58:32.870 --> 00:58:34.580
and not allowing the
activists to get in.

00:58:34.580 --> 00:58:37.300
So I'm thinking like
in countries in Asia,

00:58:37.300 --> 00:58:40.530
where a lot of the companies
are owner operator companies.

00:58:40.530 --> 00:58:42.590
They really have really
different motivations,

00:58:42.590 --> 00:58:45.290
and even though it could
be cheap on the acquirer's

00:58:45.290 --> 00:58:47.330
multiple, what are
your perspectives

00:58:47.330 --> 00:58:49.570
on why would it work
in those markets

00:58:49.570 --> 00:58:53.365
when the founders have no
reason to let anyone in?

00:58:53.365 --> 00:58:54.990
TOBIAS CARLISLE: You
might need to look

00:58:54.990 --> 00:58:57.700
at what they're doing with the
cash flows when they get them.

00:58:57.700 --> 00:59:02.010
Are they paying
them out, are they

00:59:02.010 --> 00:59:07.310
using them to expand the size
of their kingdom, are they

00:59:07.310 --> 00:59:09.710
investing them in lower
return businesses?

00:59:13.780 --> 00:59:19.690
I think that it definitely
does work in the US,

00:59:19.690 --> 00:59:22.320
because you have that tension
when somebody comes in.

00:59:22.320 --> 00:59:24.450
But I think if
you look in the US

00:59:24.450 --> 00:59:26.770
at the-- and this is
something that I looked at,

00:59:26.770 --> 00:59:29.640
the number of those companies
that are actually taken over

00:59:29.640 --> 00:59:31.640
or have some sort
of activist event

00:59:31.640 --> 00:59:33.640
occur is actually
still quite small.

00:59:33.640 --> 00:59:35.520
It's only about 1/20.

00:59:35.520 --> 00:59:39.820
And so for the other 19 it's
simply that mean reversion

00:59:39.820 --> 00:59:42.000
in the business that
generates the returns.

00:59:42.000 --> 00:59:45.910
So when you're looking at Asia,
if you're looking at Japan,

00:59:45.910 --> 00:59:48.674
for example, where it's
a fairly insular society,

00:59:48.674 --> 00:59:50.090
but there are some
sort of inroads

00:59:50.090 --> 00:59:52.911
being made by American
activists there.

00:59:52.911 --> 00:59:54.410
Even though the
period of time where

00:59:54.410 --> 00:59:56.237
there wasn't a lot
of activist activity,

00:59:56.237 --> 00:59:58.570
there still were quite good
returns to those undervalued

00:59:58.570 --> 01:00:01.210
companies, even [INAUDIBLE]
across shareholdings.

01:00:01.210 --> 01:00:03.840
And I acknowledge now that they
have been very undervalued,

01:00:03.840 --> 01:00:07.010
and maybe they're less so
now over the last few weeks.

01:00:07.010 --> 01:00:08.890
But it still has work there.

01:00:08.890 --> 01:00:12.230
I don't think it's
necessary for it to work,

01:00:12.230 --> 01:00:17.330
but there are always
metaphysical reasons

01:00:17.330 --> 01:00:19.810
outside the realm
of the backtesting

01:00:19.810 --> 01:00:22.760
that I can't answer,
and you're sort

01:00:22.760 --> 01:00:25.100
of going on faith a little bit.

01:00:25.100 --> 01:00:27.490
Perhaps if those
markets open up, too.

01:00:27.490 --> 01:00:31.090
They continue to open up and
they adopt more external type

01:00:31.090 --> 01:00:34.169
management, because it's
a globalising world.

01:00:34.169 --> 01:00:35.960
They have to sell
outside their boundaries,

01:00:35.960 --> 01:00:37.815
so they need different
types of management.

01:00:37.815 --> 01:00:40.220
AUDIENCE: Thank you
so much for your talk.

01:00:40.220 --> 01:00:41.640
It was great.

01:00:41.640 --> 01:00:42.840
TOBIAS CARLISLE: Thank you.

